ment. We only need to set up the backup device once (first three lines). This applies in all three backup cases.\r\n\r\n<strong>USE MASTER</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>GO</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sp_addumpdevice ‘disk’,’SCFULL’,’D:\\DB_Backup\\SCFULL.bak’</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKUP DATABASE sheffieldCycles to SCFULL</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>WITH FORMAT, NAME = ‘SCFull’,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION = ‘Full Backup’</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Daily:</strong>\r\n\r\nA differential backup. At the end of each day a backup of any changes since the last full backup should be made. This means we can never lose more than the current days changes. The following T-SQL would achieve this in the test environment.\r\n\r\n<strong>USE MASTER</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>GO</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sp_addumpdevice ‘disk’,’SCCHANGE’,’D:\\DB_Backup\\SCCHANGE.bak’</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKUP DATABASE sheffieldCycles to SCHANGE</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>With DIFFERENTIAL, NOINIT</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Every 15 mins:</strong>\r\n\r\nA transaction log backup. Every change (transaction) is stored in the database log backing up this log every 15 minutes allows us to roll the database back to any time (within 15 minutes) of the current day. The following T-SQL would achieve this in the test environment.\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKUP LOG sheffieldCycles to SCHANGE</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>WITH FORMAT, NAME = ‘SCHANGE’,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION = ‘Log Backup’</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Security</strong>\r\n\r\nBy creating roles such as sales, dispatch, accounts or manager, and then applying specific database permissions we can control access to only what is needed by the role. Figure 1 shows how table and column permissions can be assigned to roles using SQL Server Management StudioUsers can be created with login names and passwords for security (figure 2). Users can then be assigned roles and inherit permissions from the roles as shown in figure 3.','SQL Server','','trash','open','open','','sql-server__trashed','','','2018-02-02 10:39:13','2018-02-02 10:39:13','',0,'http://homepages.shu.ac.uk/~b6031184/selfix_technology/?p=95',0,'post','',0),(96,5,'2017-12-08 09:27:00','2017-12-08 09:27:00','<strong>Sheffield Cycles Backup and Security Proposal</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Database Admin and Data Sources</strong>\r\n\r\nWaqas Hussain, Robert Baggaley\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Backup</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Weekly:</strong>\r\n\r\nFull database backup. This could be to the cloud or to a local server, but an off-site copy of the backup should also be performed. The following T-SQL would achieve this in the test environment. We only need to set up the backup device once (first three lines). This applies in all three backup cases.\r\n\r\n<strong>USE MASTER</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>GO</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sp_addumpdevice ‘disk’,’SCFULL’,’D:\\DB_Backup\\SCFULL.bak’</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKUP DATABASE sheffieldCycles to SCFULL</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>WITH FORMAT, NAME = ‘SCFull’,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION = ‘Full Backup’</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Daily:</strong>\r\n\r\nA differential backup. At the end of each day a backup of any changes since the last full backup should be made. This means we can never lose more than the current days changes. The following T-SQL would achieve this in the test environment.\r\n\r\n<strong>USE MASTER</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>GO</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sp_addumpdevice ‘disk’,’SCCHANGE’,’D:\\DB_Backup\\SCCHANGE.bak’</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKUP DATABASE sheffieldCycles to SCHANGE</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>With DIFFERENTIAL, NOINIT</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Every 15 mins:</strong>\r\n\r\nA transaction log backup. Every change (transaction) is stored in the database log backing up this log every 15 minutes allows us to roll the database back to any time (within 15 minutes) of the current day. The following T-SQL would achieve this in the test environment.\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKUP LOG sheffieldCycles to SCHANGE</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>WITH FORMAT, NAME = ‘SCHANGE’,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION = ‘Log Backup’</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Security</strong>\r\n\r\nBy creating roles such as sales, dispatch, accounts or manager, and then applying specific database permissions we can control access to only what is needed by the role. Figure 1 shows how table and column permissions can be assigned to roles using SQL Server Management StudioUsers can be created with login names and passwords for security (figure 2). Users can then be assigned roles and inherit permissions from the roles as shown in figure 3.','SQL Server','','inherit','closed','closed','','95-revision-v1','','','2017-12-08 09:27:00','2017-12-08 09:27:00','',95,'http://homepages.shu.ac.uk/~b6031184/selfix_technology/uncategorised/95-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(97,5,'2017-12-08 09:27:07','2017-12-08 09:27:07','<strong>Sheffield Cycles Backup and Security Proposal</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Database Admin and Data Sources</strong>\r\n\r\nWaqas Hussain, Robert Baggaley\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Backup</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Weekly:</strong>\r\n\r\nFull database backup. This could be to the cloud or to a local server, but an off-site copy of the backup should also be performed. The following T-SQL would achieve this in the test environment. We only need to set up the backup device once (first three lines). This applies in all three backup cases.\r\n\r\n<strong>USE MASTER</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>GO</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sp_addumpdevice ‘disk’,’SCFULL’,’D:\\DB_Backup\\SCFULL.bak’</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKUP DATABASE sheffieldCycles to SCFULL</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>WITH FORMAT, NAME = ‘SCFull’,</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION = ‘Full Backup’</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Daily:</strong>\r\n\r\nA differential backup. At the end of each day a backup of any changes since the last full bac